✅ 1. Python (Python didn’t have traditional switch until 3.10)

Use match in Python 3.10+:

x = 2

match x:
    case 1:
        print("One")
    case 2:
        print("Two")
    case _:
        print("Default")


match is Python’s version of switch.

case _ acts as default.

For older versions, use if/elif chains or dictionaries.

✅ 2. PHP

$x = 2;

switch ($x) {
    case 1:
        echo "One";
        break;
    case 2:
        echo "Two";
        break;
    default:
        echo "Default";
}


Requires break to prevent fall-through.

default is optional.

✅ 3. MATLAB

MATLAB uses switch/case like this:

x = 2;

switch x
    case 1
        disp('One')
    case 2
        disp('Two')
    otherwise
        disp('Default')
end


No break needed.

otherwise is the default case.

Ends with end.

✅ 4. Java

int x = 2;

switch (x) {
    case 1:
        System.out.println("One");
        break;
    case 2:
        System.out.println("Two");
        break;
    default:
        System.out.println("Default");
}


Requires break to avoid fall-through.

Since Java 14+, enhanced switch is available.

Java 14+ version:

switch (x) {
    case 1 -> System.out.println("One");
    case 2 -> System.out.println("Two");
    default -> System.out.println("Default");
}


✅ 5. C#

int x = 2;

switch (x) {
    case 1:
        Console.WriteLine("One");
        break;
    case 2:
        Console.WriteLine("Two");
        break;
    default:
        Console.WriteLine("Default");
        break;
}


Very similar to Java.

C# 8.0+ also supports switch expressions.

Example (C# 8+):

string result = x switch
{
    1 => "One",
    2 => "Two",
    _ => "Default"
};
Console.WriteLine(result);


✅ 6. C++

int x = 2;

switch (x) {
    case 1:
        std::cout << "One" << std::endl;
        break;
    case 2:
        std::cout << "Two" << std::endl;
        break;
    default:
        std::cout << "Default" << std::endl;
}
